comments.content:
@hrant  
I first noticed the similarity a while back when I was helping my college newspaper's new design director to re-design. He wanted to use only free or open source fonts, because he's a FOSS nut from Korea, so I insisted that we stick to at least the professionally designed typefaces. Thankfully, the body copy was easy, Bitstream Charter and Utopia are both available. Matching them with a non-crappy free sans became the priority, and that's when I realized that Univers matched perfectly. We would swap them for headlines, and it worked great.

@paragraph  
I don't have Fontlab at work, but I can show some outline examples tomorrow. But [you can download the abomination here if you want to look at the outlines yourself](http://web.archive.org/web/20131023121241/http:/dangayle.com/ftp/Utopivers.zip)

@John: thanks, I have seen them before on Karsten's website but I forgot. In fact it's unlikely I will use them as I don't have Python installed but maybe in some quiet moment… :=)

In the end, they make something similar to what Ares FontChameleon or the old Incubator did, right?  
With the difference that FontChameleon worked mostly as a blending tool, with two source typefaces.
